The idea that everything must be valued at some price is crucial to our modern economic system. This is how things work since our economy is based on the free market system where products and services are traded for currency. This model dominates the distribution of commercial products and services worldwide. Love, friendship, and other types of social contact, for example, cannot be put a price on and should not be traded for money. Public goods are things like healthcare and education that the government provides to its residents regardless of whether or not they have the means to pay for them. We live in a society where certain things are regarded "priceless," even though their monetary value isn't always taken into account. 